00:01:52.840 --> 00:01:54.420
My name is Stephanie Hannon.

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:57.560
Along with my colleagues
Eric Hysen and Payal Patel,

00:01:57.560 --> 00:02:00.670
we're crazy proud to be
here to talk with you today.

00:02:00.670 --> 00:02:04.260
We three are part of a team at
Google called Social Impact,

00:02:04.260 --> 00:02:06.510
and we apply our
engineering talent

00:02:06.510 --> 00:02:08.979
to social and
humanitarian problems

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:12.780
like improving society,
improving democracy, keeping

00:02:12.780 --> 00:02:16.090
people safe, ending
repressive censorship,

00:02:16.090 --> 00:02:19.750
and making the nonprofit
ecosystem more impactful.

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:22.690
I've been building products
at Google for almost a decade,

00:02:22.690 --> 00:02:25.710
from launching Gmail all
over the world to building

00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:28.110
maps for Europe,
Middle East, and Africa

00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:32.230
and even launching Google
Wave on this stage.

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:33.997
Anyone Wave fans?

00:02:33.997 --> 00:02:35.160
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:36.770
Thank you, thank you.

00:02:36.770 --> 00:02:38.530
But I joined this
team earlier this year

00:02:38.530 --> 00:02:42.900
because I was in awe of the
problems that need attention

00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:46.830
and also Google's commitment
with resources and people

00:02:46.830 --> 00:02:50.410
to try to solve and
make a big impact.

00:02:50.410 --> 00:02:52.830
I'd like to share two
examples of the type of work

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:56.370
our team does by taking
you back to 2012,

00:02:56.370 --> 00:03:00.330
when Hurricane Sandy hit the
Eastern seaboard just eight

00:03:00.330 --> 00:03:02.590
days before the US election.

00:03:02.590 --> 00:03:04.580
I probably don't
need to remind you

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:06.355
that Hurricane Sandy
was the deadliest

00:03:06.355 --> 00:03:08.610
and destructive of that season.

00:03:08.610 --> 00:03:13.410
Its winds spanned 1,000 miles,
and more than 268 people

00:03:13.410 --> 00:03:15.700
died in the seven
countries it touched.

00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:20.810
The damage in the US alone
was $68 billion dollars.

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:23.810
As you can see, this is
a picture of Hoboken.

00:03:23.810 --> 00:03:26.180
More than half of
Hoboken was flooded,

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:28.710
as was chunks of Staten
Island and Brooklyn

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:30.690
and lots of coastal communities.

00:03:30.690 --> 00:03:32.340
The streets were
turned into rivers,

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:35.250
and lives and
homes were ravaged.

00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:37.130
At a moment like
this, there's a lot

00:03:37.130 --> 00:03:40.090
of critical need for
information about resources.

00:03:40.090 --> 00:03:42.070
You can see this is a
picture of a Hess gas

00:03:42.070 --> 00:03:46.110
station in New Jersey where cars
lined up for hours and hours.

00:03:46.110 --> 00:03:49.390
Nobody knew where gas
was and how to get it.

00:03:49.390 --> 00:03:52.830
The Google Crisis team was able
to publish this crisis map,

00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:55.250
and all the green dots
on there represent

00:03:55.250 --> 00:03:57.430
availability in
the tri-state area.

00:03:57.430 --> 00:04:00.950
You could change it to different
types of inventory questions.

00:04:00.950 --> 00:04:04.690
And the real challenge here is
fresh, real-time information,

00:04:04.690 --> 00:04:06.330
because in a moment
like this there's

00:04:06.330 --> 00:04:08.530
not a single source
of data available.

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:11.340
So we were able to build this
by working with distributors

00:04:11.340 --> 00:04:15.030
like Hess, with
government agencies,

00:04:15.030 --> 00:04:18.910
and with crowdsourcing efforts
like GasBuddy and Maplet.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:20.660
Some of the best
sources of information

00:04:20.660 --> 00:04:22.451
were high school students
in New Jersey who

00:04:22.451 --> 00:04:24.950
were calling constantly
gas stations,

00:04:24.950 --> 00:04:26.860
and we got fresh,
real-time information.

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:28.550
And the challenge at
Google is to ingest

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:30.530
data from all these
different sources and lots

00:04:30.530 --> 00:04:33.460
of different formats,
sanitize it, and publish it

00:04:33.460 --> 00:04:35.630
to consumers in a useful way.

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:37.630
And tens of thousands of
people viewed this map,

00:04:37.630 --> 00:04:40.664
and we hope it helped
keep them safe and warm.

00:04:40.664 --> 00:04:43.080
Payal is going to talk a lot
more about our crisis efforts

00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:43.579
today.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:49.300
Another challenge was
dozens of polling locations

00:04:49.300 --> 00:04:52.420
were flooded just days
before the US election,

00:04:52.420 --> 00:04:54.640
and the government had
this incredible challenge

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:56.860
of how do we get
information out about where

00:04:56.860 --> 00:04:59.160
people should go to vote.

00:04:59.160 --> 00:05:02.990
So a company called Mobile
Commons built an SMS messaging

00:05:02.990 --> 00:05:03.490
app.

00:05:03.490 --> 00:05:04.940
It was really simple.

00:05:04.940 --> 00:05:06.590
You would SMS your
home address, and it

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:08.520
would return your
polling location.

00:05:08.520 --> 00:05:11.650
It was built in partnership
with city and state governments,

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:14.010
and it leverages the
Google Civic Information

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:17.650
API, which Eric will tell
you a lot more about today.

00:05:17.650 --> 00:05:19.890
The governor of New Jersey
and the mayor of New York

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:21.930
got out on social media
and in press conferences

00:05:21.930 --> 00:05:23.240
and promoted this.

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:25.380
And the locations were
changing hour by hour,

00:05:25.380 --> 00:05:27.850
so it was a pretty
important service.

00:05:27.850 --> 00:05:30.070
And in the days leading
up to the US election,

00:05:30.070 --> 00:05:35.340
more than 200,000 people used it
to find their polling location.

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:38.810
So Google Crisis Map and
Google Civic Information API

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:40.690
are two examples of
the work we are trying

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:43.890
to do to keep people
safe and improve society.

00:05:43.890 --> 00:05:47.970
And what's really amazing to
me is that we in this room

00:05:47.970 --> 00:05:51.540
have the ability to touch
people on a global scale

00:05:51.540 --> 00:05:54.090
with our products and services.

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:57.760
It's remarkable the amazing
amount of technology computing

00:05:57.760 --> 00:05:59.990
power that I can hold my hand.

00:05:59.990 --> 00:06:02.820
And today, over 60% of
the global population

00:06:02.820 --> 00:06:07.000
has a cell phone and more
than 3 billion people

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.410
are online with access
to the internet.

00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:14.010
Technology has already
transformed media and commerce.

00:06:14.010 --> 00:06:18.230
It has the potential to fix
democracy, improve education,

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:22.045
and secure opportunity and
happiness for all people.

00:06:22.045 --> 00:06:24.170
We, along with the community
of people in this room

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:26.560
and around the world, are
working in this space,

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:28.770
and we hope by you guys
coming to this talk

00:06:28.770 --> 00:06:30.917
today we're going to
recruit even more.

00:06:30.917 --> 00:06:33.500
And I just want to say this is
the only use of a prop all day.

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:36.260
So if you came for
sexy demos, wrong room.

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:41.550
So as we've been
working in this space,

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:44.566
we've developed three principles
that are critical to our work.

00:06:44.566 --> 00:06:46.440
I want to share them
with you, and then we'll

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:49.310
talk about them throughout
the conversation today.

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:52.850
The first is designing for
openness and interoperability.

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:55.730
If you want to work in disaster
response or civic engagement,

00:06:55.730 --> 00:06:58.070
you need to work
with governments.

00:06:58.070 --> 00:07:00.020
And there's thousands
of government entities

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:02.890
around the world, and
they're lacking incentives

00:07:02.890 --> 00:07:05.420
to open up data
in common formats.

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:07.770
So it would not be great
if we built something

00:07:07.770 --> 00:07:09.840
that worked for San
Francisco but it didn't

00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:12.880
work for Seattle
or Rio or Tokyo.

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:15.460
So thinking early
about common formats,

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:16.920
how to organize
people around them,

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:19.530
and building for openness
and interoperability

00:07:19.530 --> 00:07:24.230
and advocating for open data
has been a big part of our work.

00:07:24.230 --> 00:07:28.310
Second, in our experience,
the way open data is published

00:07:28.310 --> 00:07:31.840
is very rarely consumable
in an easy format

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:34.090
by people or by developers.

00:07:34.090 --> 00:07:37.030
And so a lot of work has
been about transforming data

00:07:37.030 --> 00:07:39.080
so that we can build
meaningful consumer product

00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:42.460
features in Google Now
Search and other places,

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:44.760
but also giving it back
to you guys in a platform

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:49.465
and through APIs so you can
do meaningful things too.

00:07:49.465 --> 00:07:51.090
And finally, a third
principle for us--

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:52.756
I noticed in the
keynote all good things

00:07:52.756 --> 00:07:54.130
come in three, right?

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:57.530
Everyone sees that--
think like a startup.

00:07:57.530 --> 00:08:00.250
So the same aggressive way
you would pursue an idea

00:08:00.250 --> 00:08:03.895
and try to fail fast, the same
attention to user segmentation

00:08:03.895 --> 00:08:06.090
and who you're serving.

00:08:06.090 --> 00:08:08.030
Google, for example--
we're working

00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:11.140
really hard on search quality
around the nonprofit ecosystem,

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:13.050
and it's a decision
whether we're

00:08:13.050 --> 00:08:15.990
trying to reach the people who
are donating and volunteering

00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:19.140
or trying to reach the people
who are looking for services.

00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:20.880
So be clear about
your user segments

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:22.620
and who you're trying to serve.

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:25.190
Also in thinking like a
startup, funding is available.

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:26.006
There's VC funding.

00:08:26.006 --> 00:08:27.130
There's foundation funding.

00:08:27.130 --> 00:08:29.730
You can build sustainable,
scalable businesses.

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:32.070
So think like a startup
as you approach this.

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:33.770
And finally, there's
tons of action

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:36.169
in this space around weekend
projects or hackathons,

00:08:36.169 --> 00:08:37.659
and that's great.

00:08:37.659 --> 00:08:39.320
More ideation is good.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:42.230
But this can also be sustainable
and scalable businesses.

00:08:42.230 --> 00:08:44.100
It can be your
full-time gig, and I

00:08:44.100 --> 00:08:47.140
hope you'll think
about that today.

00:08:47.140 --> 00:08:49.080
As we go out and advocate
and talk to groups,

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:51.190
people often ask, is
there funding available?

00:08:51.190 --> 00:08:53.160
Can I really work in the space?

00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:56.960
So you can see in this graph
from the Knight Foundation

00:08:56.960 --> 00:09:00.620
that civic tech is
on a fast growth.

00:09:00.620 --> 00:09:04.070
121 companies were
started in 2012 alone--

00:09:04.070 --> 00:09:06.330
and I apologize that the
text here is so small.

00:09:06.330 --> 00:09:09.270
So lots of activity, lots
of growth in civic tech.

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:11.890
But is funding available?

00:09:11.890 --> 00:09:15.840
So in the period from January
of 2011 to May of 2013,

00:09:15.840 --> 00:09:20.280
$431 million--
sometimes I say 2,

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:22.962
so I have to check
slides-- $431 million

00:09:22.962 --> 00:09:24.510
were invested in civic tech.

00:09:24.510 --> 00:09:26.640
And the investment comes
in all different ways.

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:29.710
The Omidyar Network did 16
investments in this space

00:09:29.710 --> 00:09:31.290
alone.

00:09:31.290 --> 00:09:34.360
Y Combinator is now
supporting civic tech startups

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:36.700
and nonprofits in its program.

00:09:36.700 --> 00:09:38.780
Alumni of the Code
for America program

00:09:38.780 --> 00:09:41.440
are starting lots of amazing
civic tech companies.

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.940
Lots of action, which is why
it's so exciting that you chose

00:09:43.940 --> 00:09:47.910
to be here with us to
talk about it today.

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:50.400
So I'm going to turn it
over soon to my colleagues.

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:52.260
We're going to talk
about these principles.

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:55.001
We're going to dig into some
stories about the work we do.

00:09:55.001 --> 00:09:57.500
And then we're really excited
to have this open conversation

00:09:57.500 --> 00:09:59.660
about how we can
work better together.

00:09:59.660 --> 00:10:00.410
And now, for Eric.

00:10:03.472 --> 00:10:04.680
ERIC HYSEN: Thank you, Steph.

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:05.930
My name's Eric Hysen.

00:10:05.930 --> 00:10:09.290
I manage our elections and
civic engagement products.

00:10:09.290 --> 00:10:11.790
I've been a part of
this team since 2009

00:10:11.790 --> 00:10:14.540
and before that worked
on political campaigns.

00:10:14.540 --> 00:10:19.420
I want to start by going
back to the 2008 US election.

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:23.460
Just six years ago but
feels a long time ago.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:27.680
So imagine you're getting
ready to vote in that election.

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:30.210
Think about the
information you might need,

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:31.880
what you would need to do.

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:33.400
One of the top
things on your list

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:35.406
is probably where you vote.

00:10:35.406 --> 00:10:37.610
If you're anything
like me, you probably

00:10:37.610 --> 00:10:41.074
think that you should go
online for this information.

00:10:41.074 --> 00:10:42.740
Unfortunately, it
turns out that, again,

00:10:42.740 --> 00:10:46.450
just six years ago, in 39
states there was no way

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:48.670
to find this information
online at all.

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:50.810
But even pausing
that for a second,

00:10:50.810 --> 00:10:52.720
let's say you were lucky.

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:54.910
You lived in one of
the 11 states that did

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:58.510
put this information
online-- say, New Hampshire.

00:10:58.510 --> 00:11:01.040
This is the service the New
Hampshire state government

00:11:01.040 --> 00:11:04.550
provides for looking up
your voting information.

00:11:04.550 --> 00:11:06.850
Try to work through it with me.

00:11:06.850 --> 00:11:08.402
You have two options here.

00:11:08.402 --> 00:11:10.110
On the left, you can
enter in a whole lot

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:12.440
of personal information
that actually

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:16.130
has nothing to do with where
you're assigned to vote at all.

00:11:16.130 --> 00:11:20.090
Or on the right, you
get to do two things.

00:11:20.090 --> 00:11:22.300
First you select your
street from a drop

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:23.940
down of every
street in the state.

00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:27.559
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:27.559 --> 00:11:29.350
And I've still never
figured this part out.

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:31.060
I've looked at this site a lot.

00:11:31.060 --> 00:11:33.690
You pick if your street
number is between 1 and 99

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:35.090
or 1 and 131.

00:11:35.090 --> 00:11:40.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:42.720
Or if you're at
all rational, you

00:11:42.720 --> 00:11:45.860
would probably come across a
site like this and give up.

00:11:45.860 --> 00:11:49.700
And that makes sense, but let's
think through the consequences

00:11:49.700 --> 00:11:51.760
of that if you're
trying to vote.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:52.800
It's Election Day.

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:54.940
You've probably seen a
lot of polling places.

00:11:54.940 --> 00:11:57.470
Maybe you passed one on
your drive into work,

00:11:57.470 --> 00:12:00.200
so you stop there
on your way home.

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:04.500
You very likely could end
up in a line like this one.

00:12:04.500 --> 00:12:06.280
You could wait in
this line, possibly

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:09.590
for hours, just
to get to the end

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:12.670
and finally figure out this
wasn't actually your polling

00:12:12.670 --> 00:12:13.820
place.

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:15.810
So the poll worker
there checking you in

00:12:15.810 --> 00:12:17.990
will probably very
happily tell you

00:12:17.990 --> 00:12:19.770
where you actually go to vote.

00:12:19.770 --> 00:12:22.310
But at this point, you've
been waiting for hours.

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:26.020
You probably have to get home to
your family or go back to work.

00:12:26.020 --> 00:12:29.330
How likely are you to
actually cast your vote?

00:12:29.330 --> 00:12:30.950
This isn't just an
individual problem.

00:12:30.950 --> 00:12:34.580
This can happen to hundreds
of thousands of people.

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:37.490
It's particularly bad for the
least advantaged among us,

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:40.660
who really don't have
this time to spare.

00:12:40.660 --> 00:12:43.150
And it's not just about
finding your polling place

00:12:43.150 --> 00:12:45.090
but about registering
to vote on time

00:12:45.090 --> 00:12:48.630
or bringing the right
forms of ID to the polls.

00:12:48.630 --> 00:12:51.710
In aggregate, what are just
frustrating experiences

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:54.780
individually can sway the
outcome of an election

00:12:54.780 --> 00:12:56.720
just because people don't
have the information

00:12:56.720 --> 00:13:00.290
they need in an easy format.

00:13:00.290 --> 00:13:02.430
So this is where
Google comes in.

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:05.180
As you might imagine, the
quality of our search results

00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:06.940
is particularly important to us.

00:13:06.940 --> 00:13:10.010
So we have a lot of people
across the company who

00:13:10.010 --> 00:13:12.690
are frequently looking through
our broad, aggregate trends,

00:13:12.690 --> 00:13:15.350
trying to be sure that we're
doing a good job of answering

00:13:15.350 --> 00:13:17.080
our users' queries.

00:13:17.080 --> 00:13:19.130
So in the run up to
the 2008 election,

00:13:19.130 --> 00:13:21.030
we had some of these
folks that kept

00:13:21.030 --> 00:13:24.130
seeing these spikes for
searches like "Where do I vote?"

00:13:24.130 --> 00:13:25.770
as elections approached.

00:13:25.770 --> 00:13:26.730
That makes sense.

00:13:26.730 --> 00:13:29.840
But like we just saw,
we really couldn't

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:32.150
do a very good job of
answering these questions,

00:13:32.150 --> 00:13:34.210
because the information
either wasn't out there

00:13:34.210 --> 00:13:36.360
or wasn't easily accessible.

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:39.390
So we decided that we had an
obligation and the ability

00:13:39.390 --> 00:13:42.310
to do much better.

00:13:42.310 --> 00:13:45.330
We set out to collect and
standardize this information

00:13:45.330 --> 00:13:48.820
and quickly ran into the fact
that, like many government

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:51.190
services in the US,
voting is actually

00:13:51.190 --> 00:13:53.520
not run at the national
level-- not even run

00:13:53.520 --> 00:13:54.680
at the state level.

00:13:54.680 --> 00:13:57.770
It's run in the thousands of
individual counties in most

00:13:57.770 --> 00:13:58.780
cases.

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:00.540
So this means that
there are thousands

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:03.250
of different government
agencies all running voting.

00:14:03.250 --> 00:14:06.000
And, of course, they
all do it differently.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.330
So rather than go
at this alone we

00:14:08.330 --> 00:14:10.930
worked with some partners,
notably the Pew Charitable

00:14:10.930 --> 00:14:13.590
Trusts, to set up a group
called the Voting Information

00:14:13.590 --> 00:14:18.030
Project to go out, collect, and
standardize this information.

00:14:18.030 --> 00:14:20.050
We expected things
to be pretty tough

00:14:20.050 --> 00:14:23.980
but were still pretty shocked
at some of what we saw.

00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:25.120
This is one example.

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:27.460
This is actually from 2012.

00:14:27.460 --> 00:14:29.645
It's unfortunately not
too much of an outlier.

00:14:29.645 --> 00:14:30.980
I really wish it were.

00:14:30.980 --> 00:14:33.580
But this is what
the team got when

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:35.550
they talked to the
election officials

00:14:35.550 --> 00:14:39.280
in Dale County, Alabama, and
asked for information on how

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:41.270
to map voters to polling places.

00:14:41.270 --> 00:14:44.250
So they got faxed
back this document,

00:14:44.250 --> 00:14:46.270
and there are a lot of problems.

00:14:46.270 --> 00:14:48.670
My favorite is here.

00:14:48.670 --> 00:14:51.530
You can see how they tried
to update this for 2012 just

00:14:51.530 --> 00:14:55.250
crossing out 2006.

00:14:55.250 --> 00:14:58.400
Problems like this
really are not uncommon

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:00.470
when dealing with
government data.

00:15:00.470 --> 00:15:04.010
One other example-- the
state of Texas, a huge state,

00:15:04.010 --> 00:15:07.120
doesn't finalize their polling
places until the Friday

00:15:07.120 --> 00:15:08.650
before the election.

00:15:08.650 --> 00:15:12.650
So you have 72 hours to collect
this, standardize it, process

00:15:12.650 --> 00:15:15.670
it, get it out to their users.

00:15:15.670 --> 00:15:17.560
But the team persevered.

00:15:17.560 --> 00:15:20.970
And in the end, we had
thousands of different files,

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:23.120
all different formats.

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:25.390
This is where our
first pillar comes in.

00:15:25.390 --> 00:15:28.590
Rather than try to deal
with them all separately,

00:15:28.590 --> 00:15:30.500
we created a
standard data format

00:15:30.500 --> 00:15:33.960
to make this easier to use, the
first-ever interoperable data

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:35.680
format for voting information.

00:15:35.680 --> 00:15:40.120
It's an XML-based format called
the VIP, Voting Information

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:43.800
Project XML spec, and here's
a little bit of how it works.

00:15:43.800 --> 00:15:45.820
Since we're at a
developer conference,

00:15:45.820 --> 00:15:47.700
I can show some XML.

00:15:47.700 --> 00:15:51.260
So polling places in
the US are assigned

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:54.190
based on these things
called street segments.

00:15:54.190 --> 00:15:57.910
Unlike most other uses of
anything related to geodata,

00:15:57.910 --> 00:16:02.520
you don't have shapefiles in
this case but tabular data

00:16:02.520 --> 00:16:06.990
that are lists of ranges
of addresses on the street,

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:08.770
even down to what
side of the street

00:16:08.770 --> 00:16:11.970
you're on, because the lines for
which polling place you go to

00:16:11.970 --> 00:16:14.350
can actually be drawn down
the middle of the street.

00:16:14.350 --> 00:16:16.100
So you need something
that's a little more

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:19.010
precise that governments
are able to use.

00:16:19.010 --> 00:16:22.240
So this XML defines a
street segment in Virginia,

00:16:22.240 --> 00:16:26.970
maps it to a precinct, and
then another part of the XML

00:16:26.970 --> 00:16:30.100
says where that
precinct goes to vote

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:33.380
and gives you that in
a structured format.

00:16:33.380 --> 00:16:36.490
Other parts of this data give us
things like ballot information,

00:16:36.490 --> 00:16:41.450
rules on voting, early vote
places, things like that.

00:16:41.450 --> 00:16:44.280
In the end, this is what
we turned this data into.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.050
This is how you can now get
voting information on Google

00:16:47.050 --> 00:16:49.150
just by entering
in your address.

00:16:49.150 --> 00:16:52.460
On the left, you get your
polling place, opening hours,

00:16:52.460 --> 00:16:55.550
a link to Google
Maps for directions.

00:16:55.550 --> 00:16:58.020
On the right, you get
information on your ballot

00:16:58.020 --> 00:17:00.190
all the way down
to the local level.

00:17:00.190 --> 00:17:02.300
This has been incredibly
successful so far.

00:17:02.300 --> 00:17:05.819
In 2012, this was used
over 24 million times

00:17:05.819 --> 00:17:10.569
to find information on how to
vote, and that's been great.

00:17:10.569 --> 00:17:13.050
We've been really amazed
at how that's been used.

00:17:13.050 --> 00:17:15.339
But as Steph said
at the beginning,

00:17:15.339 --> 00:17:19.210
our team's goal is to try to
address these social issues

00:17:19.210 --> 00:17:19.900
at large.

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:23.300
And helping Google users find
this is really important,

00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:25.990
but it's far from
the entire story.

00:17:25.990 --> 00:17:28.050
So as we were
doing this, we kept

00:17:28.050 --> 00:17:29.690
running into other
groups that were

00:17:29.690 --> 00:17:31.779
looking at similar problems.

00:17:31.779 --> 00:17:33.570
One of them was the
League of Women Voters.

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:37.690
Their voter education group, one
of the oldest in the country.

00:17:37.690 --> 00:17:40.440
If you get these thick paper
ballot guides in the mail

00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:43.850
before an election, they're the
people responsible for those.

00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:46.610
They do really great work, and
they, as a lot of folks do,

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:48.990
wanted to do more online.

00:17:48.990 --> 00:17:51.990
And they started looking at
how they could tell their users

00:17:51.990 --> 00:17:53.850
where their polling places were.

00:17:53.850 --> 00:17:57.390
So their first attempt
was to take these 51 XML

00:17:57.390 --> 00:18:01.190
files from every state and
DC and try to process them

00:18:01.190 --> 00:18:04.260
like we were doing, but
we all pretty quickly

00:18:04.260 --> 00:18:06.530
realized that was
not the best idea.

00:18:06.530 --> 00:18:09.510
It turns out it's a lot
better to have a data format

00:18:09.510 --> 00:18:12.890
than to have just jumbled
data, but it's still not

00:18:12.890 --> 00:18:14.830
all that easy to work with.

00:18:14.830 --> 00:18:18.200
And groups like the League
are not technology companies.

00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:20.310
They're civic
engagement non-profits.

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:24.020
So their time is best spent
actually engaging voters, not

00:18:24.020 --> 00:18:27.160
building data
processing pipelines.

00:18:27.160 --> 00:18:30.330
So this is where our
second principle comes in.

00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:34.020
Just having open data, even
if it's in a great format

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:36.810
and even if it's interoperable,
isn't always enough.

00:18:36.810 --> 00:18:39.670
You need to transform it to
make it useful for people

00:18:39.670 --> 00:18:42.520
to really distribute
it at scale.

00:18:42.520 --> 00:18:46.040
So to do that, we built the
Google Civic Information API.

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:48.990
This is a free API that
exposes all of that information

00:18:48.990 --> 00:18:50.420
very easily.

00:18:50.420 --> 00:18:54.270
You just pass in an address
and get back response

00:18:54.270 --> 00:18:57.850
about all the voting information
associated with that place.

00:18:57.850 --> 00:18:59.480
This is a simple request.

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:03.870
It's just the plain text
address and an ID number

00:19:03.870 --> 00:19:06.860
that's associated with what
election we're talking about.

00:19:06.860 --> 00:19:10.690
The documentation is on the
developer site down there.

00:19:10.690 --> 00:19:11.570
Here's the response.

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:12.540
It's in JSON.

00:19:12.540 --> 00:19:14.260
Again, not too complicated.

00:19:14.260 --> 00:19:18.800
You get your polling place, some
details about that, information

00:19:18.800 --> 00:19:22.970
on the contests on the ballot,
other things like that.

00:19:22.970 --> 00:19:25.660
So the API has been
very successful as well.

00:19:25.660 --> 00:19:29.290
This was actually what
powered Mobile Commons

00:19:29.290 --> 00:19:31.720
that Steph was talking about
in the beginning in making

00:19:31.720 --> 00:19:35.340
an SMS-based service for
use during Hurricane Sandy.

00:19:35.340 --> 00:19:37.580
Mobile Commons was able
to focus on dealing

00:19:37.580 --> 00:19:40.890
with building a fast,
responsive mobile interface.

00:19:40.890 --> 00:19:44.610
They let us handle all
the messy data work.

00:19:44.610 --> 00:19:46.370
The API actually
ended up being so

00:19:46.370 --> 00:19:48.430
successful we used it
for our own product.

00:19:48.430 --> 00:19:50.740
We didn't expect to do this.

00:19:50.740 --> 00:19:53.400
And the voter information
tool that I showed you

00:19:53.400 --> 00:19:56.160
a couple slides ago
is fully open source.

00:19:56.160 --> 00:19:59.010
It uses the Civic Information
API, the Maps API,

00:19:59.010 --> 00:20:02.540
and a number of other
Google Developer Tools,

00:20:02.540 --> 00:20:05.280
and you can get the code at
Google Code right up there.

00:20:08.010 --> 00:20:09.880
But after every
election, we also

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:11.940
then started hearing
from these developers

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:13.967
that they wanted to
extend their apps.

00:20:13.967 --> 00:20:15.550
No one wants to build
something that's

00:20:15.550 --> 00:20:17.460
just usable in a small moment.

00:20:17.460 --> 00:20:20.880
And they wanted to extend it
from contests and candidates

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:25.410
and polling places to elected
officials and politics

00:20:25.410 --> 00:20:26.400
every day.

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:29.130
So last year we
expanded this API

00:20:29.130 --> 00:20:31.900
to include a new
representative info query.

00:20:31.900 --> 00:20:36.390
It will give you information
on political districts,

00:20:36.390 --> 00:20:40.150
elected officials, offices
in pretty much the same way

00:20:40.150 --> 00:20:42.950
as what I just showed you.

00:20:42.950 --> 00:20:46.565
One of the top developers using
this so far is Change.org.

00:20:46.565 --> 00:20:47.940
If you haven't
seen them, they're

00:20:47.940 --> 00:20:50.070
an online petition site,
one of the biggest.

00:20:50.070 --> 00:20:52.670
And if you're familiar
with online petitions,

00:20:52.670 --> 00:20:54.870
you've probably come
across the criticism

00:20:54.870 --> 00:20:57.490
that it's hard to
take them seriously

00:20:57.490 --> 00:20:59.330
because anyone could
be signing them.

00:20:59.330 --> 00:21:02.820
You have no idea where they
live or who they actually are.

00:21:02.820 --> 00:21:06.200
So what Change.org did is they
used the Civic Information

00:21:06.200 --> 00:21:10.710
API to create a new feature that
tells an elected official how

00:21:10.710 --> 00:21:13.110
many of the people that
signed a petition actually

00:21:13.110 --> 00:21:16.080
live in their district
and are their voters.

00:21:16.080 --> 00:21:18.990
So it addresses one
of the key problems

00:21:18.990 --> 00:21:21.530
to taking the online
activism seriously

00:21:21.530 --> 00:21:25.304
and also gives elected
officials new insight

00:21:25.304 --> 00:21:26.970
into what's important
in their district.

00:21:29.776 --> 00:21:32.150
Change.org is also a great
example of the third principle

00:21:32.150 --> 00:21:35.320
that we're talking about,
think like a startup.

00:21:35.320 --> 00:21:36.820
They have a social mission.

00:21:36.820 --> 00:21:39.940
They're trying to empower
anyone to drive change

00:21:39.940 --> 00:21:42.270
through their petitions
and through their product,

00:21:42.270 --> 00:21:44.030
but they've also
thought and approached

00:21:44.030 --> 00:21:48.290
this with all the normal
tools of a startup.

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:52.610
And as a result, they have 300
paying clients and $25 million

00:21:52.610 --> 00:21:53.170
in revenue.

00:21:55.850 --> 00:21:59.300
So our team's work also
scales internationally.

00:21:59.300 --> 00:22:01.510
It was great seeing
so many of you

00:22:01.510 --> 00:22:03.400
from other parts of the world.

00:22:03.400 --> 00:22:04.900
This is an example
of a map we built

00:22:04.900 --> 00:22:07.610
for India's election,
which ended last month.

00:22:07.610 --> 00:22:10.500
We've done work like this
in over 40 countries.

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:13.170
India was one of the craziest.

00:22:13.170 --> 00:22:17.070
Their election is
the biggest election

00:22:17.070 --> 00:22:19.470
in the history of democracy.

00:22:19.470 --> 00:22:21.820
So there are over
800 million voters,

00:22:21.820 --> 00:22:25.760
and it's so many that they can't
actually all vote on one day.

00:22:25.760 --> 00:22:29.310
Instead, they split up
voting across nine days

00:22:29.310 --> 00:22:31.140
over five weeks.

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:32.970
So you can imagine
everything I was just

00:22:32.970 --> 00:22:36.730
saying for the US nine
times more complicated.

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:38.330
It was a ton of fun.

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:40.390
But what we did was
we built this map

00:22:40.390 --> 00:22:42.250
that, now that the
election's over,

00:22:42.250 --> 00:22:44.940
shows results of the
voting in every district.

00:22:44.940 --> 00:22:49.050
But before that, users could
enter in their zip code

00:22:49.050 --> 00:22:52.930
and find candidates that are
running in their district.

00:22:52.930 --> 00:22:55.550
We presented a lot of
information that we aggregated

00:22:55.550 --> 00:22:57.970
about those candidates,
including something

00:22:57.970 --> 00:23:00.440
that I was surprised to learn
was particularly relevant

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:03.320
for Indian politics, the
candidates' criminal histories.

00:23:03.320 --> 00:23:05.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:05.340 --> 00:23:10.000
So you can see this guy was the
incumbent member of parliament

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:11.640
in New Delhi.

00:23:11.640 --> 00:23:14.640
You can see that he had a
criminal case against him.

00:23:14.640 --> 00:23:16.100
When he was in
parliament, he only

00:23:16.100 --> 00:23:19.650
actually showed up
37% of the time.

00:23:19.650 --> 00:23:22.470
And then he in last
month's election

00:23:22.470 --> 00:23:24.170
ended up getting
kicked out of office.

00:23:24.170 --> 00:23:28.230
He only got 18% of the vote.

00:23:28.230 --> 00:23:31.130
Our API that I mentioned,
the Civic Information API,

00:23:31.130 --> 00:23:32.980
is currently US only.

00:23:32.980 --> 00:23:34.744
But there are
developers worldwide--

00:23:34.744 --> 00:23:36.160
hopefully many of
you in this room

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:38.680
as well-- that are
doing work like this

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:40.920
and that are also building
tools to make it easier

00:23:40.920 --> 00:23:42.980
to get involved anywhere.

00:23:42.980 --> 00:23:46.960
One of those examples
of many is Poplus.

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:50.860
This is a group that started
when developers in the UK

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:54.250
and in Chile were talking
and working together

00:23:54.250 --> 00:23:55.850
and realized that
they were building

00:23:55.850 --> 00:23:57.880
very similar tools
that were just

00:23:57.880 --> 00:23:59.760
launched in different countries.

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:02.350
So they started a
set of components

00:24:02.350 --> 00:24:07.000
that are reusable and
interoperable, customizable,

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:10.510
fully open sourced that let
