00:24:51.980 --> 00:24:55.248
How many of you
recognize this screen?

00:24:55.248 --> 00:24:58.010
OK, a good number of hands.

00:24:58.010 --> 00:25:00.920
You probably also remember
the long, shrieking sound

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:03.150
that played with it.

00:25:03.150 --> 00:25:05.490
This is the Emergency
Broadcast System

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:08.350
originating from
the 1960s that used

00:25:08.350 --> 00:25:10.870
traditional media
such as television

00:25:10.870 --> 00:25:15.850
and radio as the primary
means for alerting authorities

00:25:15.850 --> 00:25:19.370
to get critical information
such as tornado warnings

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:22.770
out to the affected public.

00:25:22.770 --> 00:25:25.570
Now, fast forward to 2012.

00:25:25.570 --> 00:25:28.730
And some of you might
recognize this message,

00:25:28.730 --> 00:25:36.030
which also has a loud, blaring
tone that plays with it.

00:25:36.030 --> 00:25:39.000
There are now wireless
emergency alerts

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.360
that allow authorities
to geographically target

00:25:42.360 --> 00:25:46.710
text-like messages to get
critical information out using

00:25:46.710 --> 00:25:48.920
cell towers.

00:25:48.920 --> 00:25:53.010
Now, while these alerts are very
effective to let people know

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:55.690
when they're in danger,
they have their limitations

00:25:55.690 --> 00:25:59.000
as to providing details
about this emergency

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:03.990
situation and really
further actionable content.

00:26:03.990 --> 00:26:06.340
So people usually
turn to the internet

00:26:06.340 --> 00:26:09.560
to get this additional
information.

00:26:09.560 --> 00:26:12.090
Now, step back two years ago.

00:26:12.090 --> 00:26:15.800
Let's say you're in
central Tennessee

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:18.310
and you hear a siren go off.

00:26:18.310 --> 00:26:20.580
You think it might be a tornado.

00:26:20.580 --> 00:26:23.690
You're not sure, so you
turn to Google Search

00:26:23.690 --> 00:26:26.940
and you search, "Is
there a tornado?"

00:26:26.940 --> 00:26:30.650
Traditional search results
actually weren't that relevant.

00:26:30.650 --> 00:26:33.160
There wasn't any mention
of the tornado warning

00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:36.100
that was just
issued moments ago.

00:26:36.100 --> 00:26:39.750
It shouldn't be this difficult
to find critical information

00:26:39.750 --> 00:26:43.500
when minutes count,
and this is the problem

00:26:43.500 --> 00:26:46.980
that our team set out to solve.

00:26:46.980 --> 00:26:50.990
We've done this by building an
emergency broadcast platform

00:26:50.990 --> 00:26:55.240
for the internet
called Public Alerts.

00:26:55.240 --> 00:26:59.520
It aggregates, ranks, and
surfaces emergency messages

00:26:59.520 --> 00:27:03.320
like this tornado warning
into everyday tools people

00:27:03.320 --> 00:27:08.250
use, such as Search,
within minutes of issuance.

00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:11.800
Now, as you can imagine,
a major component

00:27:11.800 --> 00:27:13.710
in building this
type of platform

00:27:13.710 --> 00:27:17.600
is actually getting the
authoritative content.

00:27:17.600 --> 00:27:21.710
So how did we go about doing
this in a scalable way?

00:27:21.710 --> 00:27:24.640
Every alert issuer
has their own means

00:27:24.640 --> 00:27:31.960
of creating alerts and their
own dissemination mechanism.

00:27:31.960 --> 00:27:33.560
Some have a Twitter feed.

00:27:33.560 --> 00:27:35.920
Some have a website.

00:27:35.920 --> 00:27:38.230
Some don't have any
information online at all.

00:27:40.890 --> 00:27:43.800
It'd be much easier if
there was a standard

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:46.570
that these alert issuers
used, and it turns out

00:27:46.570 --> 00:27:47.360
there actually is.

00:27:47.360 --> 00:27:51.220
It's called the Common
Alerting Protocol, CAP.

00:27:51.220 --> 00:27:54.530
About 13 years ago CAP was
designed in consultation

00:27:54.530 --> 00:27:57.540
with over 100
emergency managers,

00:27:57.540 --> 00:28:01.670
and it's been adopted as
an international standard.

00:28:01.670 --> 00:28:04.940
So why is this
standard important?

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:09.340
Well, if data providers can
create a RSS or Atom feed

00:28:09.340 --> 00:28:13.510
with all of their content
in the CAP format,

00:28:13.510 --> 00:28:17.310
then it becomes easy to
exchange this information

00:28:17.310 --> 00:28:20.920
across various platforms.

00:28:20.920 --> 00:28:23.330
So let's look at an example.

00:28:23.330 --> 00:28:26.020
This is an example of a
tsunami warning issued

00:28:26.020 --> 00:28:32.800
by BMKG, the official alerting
authority in Indonesia.

00:28:32.800 --> 00:28:35.870
This is the alert in
the raw text format,

00:28:35.870 --> 00:28:39.620
and those of you that can
read Bahasa Indonesian

00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:43.280
could tell that this has
really useful content.

00:28:43.280 --> 00:28:47.100
But it's difficult to
machine parse as is.

00:28:47.100 --> 00:28:51.700
Now, here's the same
tsunami warning in CAP.

00:28:51.700 --> 00:28:56.270
CAP is an XML-based alerting
spec that normalizes the format

00:28:56.270 --> 00:29:00.370
and provides a standard and
flexible way to target alerts

00:29:00.370 --> 00:29:02.940
by dimensions such
as language, event

00:29:02.940 --> 00:29:06.230
type, a headline,
and description.

00:29:08.840 --> 00:29:11.640
And again, like Eric and
Steph mentioned earlier,

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:16.270
building a product around a
standard is important for us

00:29:16.270 --> 00:29:18.930
because it plays a
critical role in designing

00:29:18.930 --> 00:29:20.390
for openness and
interoperability.

00:29:23.610 --> 00:29:26.150
Our team has really
embraced the CAP standard

00:29:26.150 --> 00:29:29.860
and are doing as much as we
can to drive adoption globally.

00:29:29.860 --> 00:29:33.050
We've served over
half a million alerts

00:29:33.050 --> 00:29:36.000
from 17 different alert
providers across seven

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:38.904
different countries and in
six different languages,

00:29:38.904 --> 00:29:40.195
and this is just the beginning.

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:48.070
So now in 2014, nearly a decade
since the devastating Indian

00:29:48.070 --> 00:29:53.520
Ocean tsunami, how do people get
emergency information online?

00:29:53.520 --> 00:29:58.010
Well, if you're in the coastal
region of northern Sumatra

00:29:58.010 --> 00:30:02.590
in Indonesia and have the
Google Search app installed

00:30:02.590 --> 00:30:06.180
on your Android or
iOS device, your phone

00:30:06.180 --> 00:30:08.890
would buzz to notify you
that there is a tsunami

00:30:08.890 --> 00:30:13.620
warning in effect, and you
could take action on it.

00:30:13.620 --> 00:30:15.980
You'd also be given
relevant information

00:30:15.980 --> 00:30:19.200
about the situation such
as estimated arrival

00:30:19.200 --> 00:30:23.490
times and wave heights in
a familiar, easy-to-consume

00:30:23.490 --> 00:30:25.400
format.

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:28.040
Again, this is not
just about getting

00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:32.530
the authoritative content but
really transforming that data

00:30:32.530 --> 00:30:35.530
and making it useful.

00:30:35.530 --> 00:30:38.790
Similarly if you're
in Sanmin, Taiwan,

00:30:38.790 --> 00:30:43.945
you're notified via Now if
there's an oncoming typhoon.

00:30:43.945 --> 00:30:47.550
Or if you're in
Timbiqui, Colombia,

00:30:47.550 --> 00:30:49.560
during rainy season
and want to check

00:30:49.560 --> 00:30:51.700
if you're affected by
a landslide warning,

00:30:51.700 --> 00:30:54.690
you can quickly find that
authoritative information

00:30:54.690 --> 00:30:56.120
and take action to stay safe.

00:30:58.640 --> 00:31:00.530
Since we've launched
Public Alerts,

00:31:00.530 --> 00:31:02.310
we've received
feedback from users

00:31:02.310 --> 00:31:05.640
stating that they were
notified and able to get

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:09.780
relevant information about
the situation they were in

00:31:09.780 --> 00:31:14.980
and take actions such as
seeking shelter to stay safe.

00:31:14.980 --> 00:31:18.570
Other users have said that this
was the only way they learned

00:31:18.570 --> 00:31:22.020
about the situation they were in
because they're mobile phone is

00:31:22.020 --> 00:31:25.010
their only means for
staying connected.

00:31:25.010 --> 00:31:30.560
So now, what can you as
developers do to help?

00:31:30.560 --> 00:31:33.930
Well, what you're
developing or your product

00:31:33.930 --> 00:31:35.540
might be where
some of your users

00:31:35.540 --> 00:31:40.000
spend a majority of their
time, and therefore it

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.960
can become a distribution
point for emergency alerts.

00:31:44.960 --> 00:31:48.100
You can help keep your
user community safety

00:31:48.100 --> 00:31:51.530
by integrating alerts
into your product.

00:31:51.530 --> 00:31:55.050
One way for you to do this
is to subscribe to our Alert

00:31:55.050 --> 00:31:58.780
Hub, which is where we
host all the official data

00:31:58.780 --> 00:32:03.780
feeds that we've onboarded
in their raw format.

00:32:03.780 --> 00:32:06.940
Alert Hub is open to
the developer community,

00:32:06.940 --> 00:32:10.570
and it follows the
PubSubHubbub protocol.

00:32:10.570 --> 00:32:13.490
You could also check out
the current publisher

00:32:13.490 --> 00:32:18.390
feeds that we have
available at the second URL.

00:32:18.390 --> 00:32:20.390
Or if you're
interested in accessing

00:32:20.390 --> 00:32:22.760
Public Alerts at a
higher level, you

00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:27.360
can become a beta tester
of our Public Alerts API.

00:32:27.360 --> 00:32:32.980
You can see the API in
action at this demo URL.

00:32:32.980 --> 00:32:36.830
The demo site gives you a
map list and a list view

00:32:36.830 --> 00:32:40.500
of all the current alerts
that are accessible,

00:32:40.500 --> 00:32:44.770
and on the right you
can see JSON output.

00:32:44.770 --> 00:32:46.630
If you click on any
of the active alerts,

00:32:46.630 --> 00:32:51.040
you're then directed to
the Alert Details page.

00:32:51.040 --> 00:32:54.190
And if at any given time you
want to see what alerts are

00:32:54.190 --> 00:33:03.320
active in our database, you can
go to google.org/publicalerts.

00:33:03.320 --> 00:33:05.540
Apart from Public Alerts,
I want to quickly run

00:33:05.540 --> 00:33:09.750
through a few other projects
that our team works on.

00:33:09.750 --> 00:33:12.220
These are all open
source projects.

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:13.800
One, Person Finder.

00:33:13.800 --> 00:33:17.370
It's a tool that helps people
reconnect with their loved ones

00:33:17.370 --> 00:33:20.640
during the aftermath
of a disaster.

00:33:20.640 --> 00:33:24.010
Crisis Map, which is a
rich, Geo Mashup tool

00:33:24.010 --> 00:33:27.270
designed to share
critical content,

00:33:27.270 --> 00:33:30.360
and it's optimized
for mobile use.

00:33:30.360 --> 00:33:34.140
And finally, we also
had a Java CAP library

00:33:34.140 --> 00:33:36.760
that can be used for
creating, parsing,

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:41.380
and validating CAP alert feeds.

00:33:41.380 --> 00:33:45.160
Now, I want to quickly
switch gears and highlight

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:49.650
a couple of projects outside
of Google that were developed

00:33:49.650 --> 00:33:52.350
by programmers during
a disaster situation

00:33:52.350 --> 00:33:54.550
and really had a high impact.

00:33:54.550 --> 00:33:57.180
I'm sharing these
examples to give you

00:33:57.180 --> 00:34:00.050
all an idea of how
high-impact tools can

00:34:00.050 --> 00:34:05.290
be developed in a
crisis situation.

00:34:05.290 --> 00:34:09.810
This is an image from March
2011 in Fukushima, Japan,

00:34:09.810 --> 00:34:12.940
after the massive
magnitude 9.0 earthquake

00:34:12.940 --> 00:34:15.075
struck followed by a
catastrophic tsunami.

00:34:18.290 --> 00:34:21.090
Within the developer
community in Japan,

00:34:21.090 --> 00:34:24.969
there were nationwide
hackathons for programmers

00:34:24.969 --> 00:34:29.139
that wanted to apply their
technical skills to help those

00:34:29.139 --> 00:34:31.929
that were affected
by the disaster.

00:34:31.929 --> 00:34:33.770
One of the apps
that was developed

00:34:33.770 --> 00:34:36.949
was Wind from Fukushima.

00:34:36.949 --> 00:34:40.610
This app was basically
a mobile emergency kit

00:34:40.610 --> 00:34:43.010
for those affected by
the nuclear power plant

00:34:43.010 --> 00:34:45.250
explosion in Fukushima.

00:34:45.250 --> 00:34:48.370
It calculated radiation
levels around the area,

00:34:48.370 --> 00:34:52.130
taking into account wind
speed and direction.

00:34:52.130 --> 00:34:54.989
It also provided users with
the resource information,

00:34:54.989 --> 00:34:59.470
such as where they could
find clean water and food.

00:34:59.470 --> 00:35:02.850
In order to develop this app,
official, accurate content

00:35:02.850 --> 00:35:05.460
again was critical.

00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:08.650
The developer used
openly-available radiation data

00:35:08.650 --> 00:35:12.140
provided by local government
ministries and the power

00:35:12.140 --> 00:35:14.920
companies.

00:35:14.920 --> 00:35:19.140
The raw data was in a
difficult-to-consume format,

00:35:19.140 --> 00:35:23.320
so he took out
the relevant data,

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:26.960
matched it up with relevant
user-generated data,

00:35:26.960 --> 00:35:28.560
and was able to
present it to users

00:35:28.560 --> 00:35:31.210
in an easy-to-consume format.

00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:34.120
Again, this is an example
of taking open data

00:35:34.120 --> 00:35:37.890
and transforming it
to become useful.

00:35:37.890 --> 00:35:40.300
This app was specifically
built for Fukushima.

00:35:40.300 --> 00:35:42.910
And while it was not
necessarily scalable,

00:35:42.910 --> 00:35:46.750
it had an impact on the
residents in Fukushima

00:35:46.750 --> 00:35:49.940
in that many relied on
it on a day-to-day basis

00:35:49.940 --> 00:35:53.390
to help guide them
and stay protected.

00:35:53.390 --> 00:35:55.140
Another tool I want
to quickly highlight

00:35:55.140 --> 00:35:58.690
was one that was used
during Hurricane Sandy.

00:35:58.690 --> 00:36:02.790
A major challenge during the
recovery phase of a disaster

00:36:02.790 --> 00:36:06.940
is managing the influx of
volunteers and the immense work

00:36:06.940 --> 00:36:11.720
that needs to be done on the
ground in an organized way.

00:36:11.720 --> 00:36:14.390
This is the problem
Crisis Cleanup solves.

00:36:14.390 --> 00:36:17.400
It's a collaborative work
order management system

00:36:17.400 --> 00:36:22.150
for disaster recovery agencies.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:26.300
It uses a
craigslist-like approach

00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:29.260
in that any
organization that knows

00:36:29.260 --> 00:36:32.320
of work that needs to
be done can submit it

00:36:32.320 --> 00:36:35.500
and then any organization
with the capacity

00:36:35.500 --> 00:36:39.980
to take that work on accepts
it and gets to help right away.

00:36:42.690 --> 00:36:44.990
Crisis Cleanup is a
really good example

00:36:44.990 --> 00:36:48.500
of an open source tool that
thought like a startup.

00:36:48.500 --> 00:36:53.550
They were passionate
about an idea,

00:36:53.550 --> 00:36:57.130
were aggressive about
getting funding,

00:36:57.130 --> 00:36:59.340
and built a scalable tool.

00:36:59.340 --> 00:37:02.400
It's helped over
10,000 households

00:37:02.400 --> 00:37:06.380
across 13 different disasters
in the US, the Philippines,

00:37:06.380 --> 00:37:09.095
Australia, and India.

